<head ><bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg015' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 15</bibl></head>
<p >(<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, <title >For the Liberty of the People of <placeName  key='Rhodes'>Rhodes</placeName></title>; see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). <placeName  key='Rhodes'>Rhodes</placeName> had been one of <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName>’ allies before the so-called <soCalled >Social War</soCalled>, in which <placeName  key='Rhodes'>Rhodes</placeName>, <placeName  key='Cos'>Cos</placeName>, and <placeName  key='Chios'>Chios</placeName> revolted against Athenian control. After the war ended, in <date  when='-0355'>355 BCE</date>, <name  type='person'>Mausolus</name> the satrap (governer ruling on behalf of the Persian King) of <placeName  key='Caria'>Caria</placeName>, intervened in Rhodian affairs and established a oligarchic government. The democratic party at <placeName  key='Rhodes'>Rhodes</placeName> appealed to <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> to help. In this speech, probably delivered in <date  when='-0351'>351 BCE</date>, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> attempts to convince the Athenian <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term> to help reestablish democracy on <placeName  key='Rhodes'>Rhodes</placeName>. The speech was unsuccessful, perhaps because the Athenians did not dare to risk a war with <placeName  key='Caria'>Caria</placeName> and the Persians. (Source for dates: <bibl >J.H. Vince, <title >Demosthenes I</title> [Cambridge, Mass.; Loeb Classical Library; 1930] 411</bibl>). </p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
